language Essence 1.3

$ Social Golfers Problem — Formulation 7: Matrix of Functions
$
$ Domain:  matrix indexed by [int(1..w)] of function (total) Golfers --> int(1..g)
$
$ Information carried by the domain:
$   - Each week maps every golfer to a group number (totality)
$   - Every golfer is assigned exactly one group per week (function semantics)
$   - Coverage is implicit: total function means every golfer is assigned
$
$ Information NOT carried (must be constrained explicitly):
$   - Group sizes: the function does not enforce that each group gets exactly s golfers
$   (A total function guarantees every golfer is assigned but not that groups are balanced.)
$
$ Explicit constraints needed:
$   1. Group size constraint: each group has exactly s golfers
$   2. Pairing constraint: no pair shares a group more than once
$
$ Compared to Formulations 1–6:
$   - Perspective shift: golfer-centric rather than group-centric. Instead of
$     asking "which golfers are in this group?", we ask "which group is this
$     golfer in?"
$   - Totality gives us coverage for free, but group sizes must be explicit.
$   - Disjointness is automatic: a function assigns each golfer to exactly one group.

given w, g, s : int(1..)

letting nGolfers be g * s
letting Golfers be new type of size nGolfers

find sched : matrix indexed by [int(1..w)] of function (total) Golfers --> int(1..g)

$ Group size constraint: each group in each week has exactly s golfers
such that
    forAll i : int(1..w) .
        forAll j : int(1..g) .
            (sum p : Golfers . toInt(sched[i](p) = j)) = s,

$ Pairing constraint: no two golfers share a group more than once
such that
    forAll p1 : Golfers .
        forAll p2 : Golfers .
            p1 != p2 ->
            (sum i : int(1..w) .
                toInt(sched[i](p1) = sched[i](p2))
            ) <= 1
